# Garbage Collection

Garbage collection belongs right after object pointers in the tutorial because object pointers create the problem that GC solves.

As long as your values are only plain integers, lifetime is easy.

As soon as values can point to heap objects, you must decide:

- who owns those objects
- when dead objects are reclaimed
- how compiled code keeps live pointers safe

That is what this chapter is about.

## What Garbage Collection Is Solving

A garbage collector reclaims heap objects that are no longer reachable.

The key word is reachable.

An object is usually considered live if it can still be found from a set of roots.

Typical roots include:

- globals
- local variables in active frames
- closure environments
- objects referenced by the microtask queue
- temporary values stored in runtime-managed stacks

If an object is not reachable from any root, the collector can reclaim it.

## Why JIT Code Makes GC Harder

An interpreter often keeps most live values in obvious runtime structures:

- a value stack
- call frames
- heap objects
- global tables

That makes root discovery easier.

A JIT adds a new problem:

Live pointers may now exist in native machine state.

For example:

- a value may be sitting in a register
- a temporary pointer may be spilled to the native stack
- a helper call may happen while those values are still live

If the GC cannot find those pointers, it may free live objects.

That usually leads to memory corruption or mysterious crashes.

## Root Discovery

Every GC needs a strategy for finding roots.

The main options are:

- exact root tracking
- conservative root scanning
- a restricted design where JIT code keeps roots only in VM-visible places

### Exact Root Tracking

Exact tracking means the runtime knows precisely:

- which stack locations contain pointers
- which registers contain pointers
- what each pointer refers to

This is powerful, but it requires more infrastructure.

For JIT code, exact collection often means stack maps or safepoint metadata.

### Conservative Scanning

Conservative scanning means:

- inspect machine stack memory
- treat anything that looks like a heap pointer as maybe-live

This is easier to bootstrap, but it has trade-offs:

- dead objects may stay alive longer
- moving collectors become much harder
- precision is lower

### Keep JIT Roots In VM-Owned Structures

For a hobby baseline JIT, a very practical strategy is:

- keep real language values in VM-managed stacks or frames
- use native registers mostly for transient transport
- only call into allocation or GC-relevant helpers at controlled boundaries

This greatly reduces the amount of native-state root tracking you need at first.

It is not the most optimized design, but it is much easier to keep correct.

## Safepoints

A safepoint is a place where the runtime knows it is safe to run GC.

Common safepoint candidates are:

- before or after runtime helper calls
- loop back-edges
- function prologues and epilogues
- allocation slow paths

At a safepoint, the runtime needs enough information to find all live roots.

For a baseline JIT, this often means:

- VM stacks are already synchronized
- temporary native state is minimized or spilled in a known way

This is another reason baseline JITs like runtime stub boundaries so much. They are natural places to define safepoints.

## Moving And Non-Moving Collectors

Not all collectors move objects.

That distinction matters a lot to JIT code.

### Non-Moving Collection

With a non-moving collector, object addresses stay stable.

That makes a beginner JIT much simpler because:

- native code can hold raw object pointers more easily
- no pointer rewriting is needed during compaction
- stack-map pressure is lower

This is why a simple mark-and-sweep collector is often a good first design for a hobby engine.

### Moving Collection

With a moving collector, objects may change addresses during collection.

That can improve fragmentation and performance, but it requires more machinery:

- all roots must be found exactly enough to update them
- runtime data structures must be patchable
- JIT-held pointers must be visible or reconstructible

If you want a moving collector later, that is easier once the engine already has:

- clear root tracking
- clear safepoints
- a stable VM value representation

## Write Barriers

As soon as you move toward:

- generational GC
- incremental GC
- concurrent GC

write barriers become important.

A write barrier is code that runs when one object stores a reference to another object.

The collector may need that information to maintain invariants.

This matters for JIT code because:

- property stores may need barriers
- array element writes may need barriers
- closure environment updates may need barriers

In a baseline JIT, it is often simplest to put barrier logic in runtime helpers first.

Then the JIT can call a stub for complex stores instead of inlining the barrier immediately.

## Closures, Queues, And Promises Are Also GC Clients

GC is not just about plain objects.

The collector must also understand:

- closure cells
- function objects
- promise reaction records
- queued jobs that keep callbacks alive

That is why the collector is really part of the whole runtime model, not just the object allocator.

## A Good Beginner Strategy

For a hobby engine, a very strong first GC strategy is:

1. use a non-moving collector
2. keep roots in VM-visible stacks and frames
3. make helper calls into natural safepoints
4. avoid holding long-lived hidden pointers only in native registers
5. add exact metadata later if you need a moving or more optimized collector

This is slower than a highly tuned production design, but much easier to debug.

